    <section id="iq-equation" class="reveal">
      <h2>The IQ Equation</h2>

      <p>The cognitive consequences of mild-to-moderate maternal iodine deficiency are measured, real, and irreversible in affected children.</p>

      <p>The Avon Longitudinal Study of Parents and Children (ALSPAC) — one of the most comprehensive birth cohort studies ever conducted — found that children of mothers with mild iodine deficiency in early pregnancy (defined as a UIC below 150 μg/L) showed significantly lower IQ scores at age 8 and poorer reading ability at age 9 compared to children of iodine-sufficient mothers. The effect size was not enormous — the IQ difference was approximately 3 points in the mildly deficient group — but it was statistically robust, present after adjustment for multiple confounders, and population-attributable fraction calculations suggested it was affecting a substantial fraction of the study's children.</p>

      <p>Three IQ points, on first consideration, does not sound alarming. At the population level, it is staggering. The ALSPAC study population represented a developed-country birth cohort. If a 3-point IQ shift is occurring in UK children of mildly iodine-deficient mothers, and if 23–59% of American pregnant women have inadequate iodine status, the aggregate cognitive impact is not a rounding error in population intelligence — it is a measurable suppression of cognitive capacity in the next generation.</p>

      <p>A 2025 review in <em>Nutrients</em> confirmed a U-shaped relationship: both insufficient and excessive iodine exposure during pregnancy may impair optimal brain development. Excessive iodine — particularly in women with underlying thyroid autoimmunity, in whom high iodine intake can trigger or worsen autoimmune hypothyroidism — carries its own risks. The therapeutic window is real: the recommendation for pregnant women is 220–250 μg/day, which should ideally come from a combination of iodized salt and a prenatal supplement containing at least 150 μg of iodine. The American Thyroid Association recommends a prenatal vitamin containing 150 μg of iodide (not iodate, and not from kelp, whose iodine content is variable and sometimes dangerously excessive).</p>

      <p>The fact that many popular prenatal vitamins do not contain any iodine, and that obstetric providers rarely discuss iodine supplementation with pregnant patients, represents a meaningful failure in prenatal care.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Three IQ points, on first consideration, does not sound alarming. At the population level, it is staggering."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="autism-signal" class="reveal">
      <h2>Maternal Hypothyroidism and the Autism Signal</h2>

      <p>Part 1's overview article first raised the thyroid-autism connection. Part 4 is where it deserves the full examination it has earned.</p>

      <p>A study published in November 2025 in <em>The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology &amp; Metabolism</em> by researchers at Ben-Gurion University of the Negev tracked a retrospective Israeli cohort of mothers and offspring. The findings: children of mothers with hypothyroidism that persisted across multiple trimesters showed more than a twofold increased risk of autism spectrum disorder (ASD) diagnosis, compared to children of euthyroid mothers. Crucially, the elevated risk was present specifically in mothers with persistent, inadequately controlled hypothyroidism — not in mothers whose hypothyroidism was treated and controlled. Adequately treated hypothyroidism was not associated with elevated ASD risk.</p>

      <p>This is a highly specific finding. It says: the thyroid disease is not the variable. The uncontrolled thyroid hormone deficiency is the variable. This distinction points toward a causal mechanism — thyroid hormone insufficiency at critical neurodevelopmental windows — rather than a shared genetic or confounded association. And it carries a direct clinical implication: identifying and adequately treating maternal hypothyroidism during pregnancy would, according to this model, reduce the risk of ASD in offspring.</p>

      <p>The PFAS pathway connects here. The MARBLES birth cohort study at UC Davis, examining 151 pregnant women who later had children with ASD, typical development, or non-typical development, found that prenatal PFAS exposures differentially affected maternal thyroid function based on child neurodevelopmental outcomes. The thyroid disruption mechanism is not a coincidence in this context. PFAS disrupts maternal thyroid function. Disrupted maternal thyroid function impairs fetal neurodevelopment. Impaired fetal neurodevelopment elevates ASD risk.</p>

      <p>This is a three-link chain, each link of which has independent evidential support. Whether PFAS-mediated thyroid disruption is a meaningful contributor to rising ASD rates — alongside the genetic, environmental, and diagnostic expansion factors that are clearly operating — is not yet formally established in causal terms. But the convergence of three independent lines of evidence around the same pathway is sufficiently strong that dismissing it requires a positive argument, not just uncertainty.</p>

      <p>Maternal thyroid autoimmunity — the presence of TPO antibodies — adds another dimension. A Finnish case-control study found that maternal TPO antibody positivity during pregnancy was associated with an odds ratio of 1.78 for ASD diagnosis in offspring. Women with TPO-Ab positivity show blunted thyroidal response to human chorionic gonadotropin in early gestation, resulting in lower free T4 and higher TSH compared to antibody-negative women. Thyroid autoimmunity may be contributing to ASD risk through the same pathway of functional thyroid hormone insufficiency at critical developmental windows, without the mother necessarily meeting clinical criteria for hypothyroidism.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="miscarriage-preterm-birth" class="reveal">
      <h2>Thyroid Hormone in Miscarriage and Preterm Birth</h2>

      <p>The pregnancy consequences of thyroid dysfunction extend well beyond the ASD question to miscarriage, preterm birth, and obstetric complications.</p>

      <p>The 2024 ASRM guideline on subclinical hypothyroidism in the infertile female population notes that inadequate treatment of subclinical hypothyroidism can lead to infertility, miscarriage, and adverse obstetrical and neurodevelopmental outcomes. The mechanism involves thyroid hormone's role in endometrial receptivity and implantation biology: T3 receptors are expressed in the endometrium and decidua, and their activation is required for the molecular changes that enable embryo implantation and placentation.</p>

      <p>Preeclampsia, placental abruption, and preterm delivery are significantly more common in women with untreated subclinical hypothyroidism during the first trimester. The risks are most elevated when SCH is defined at the lower TSH threshold of 2.5 mIU/L — the threshold recommended for pregnant women by the American Thyroid Association specifically because the normal physiological TSH range shifts lower during pregnancy under the influence of hCG stimulation of the thyroid.</p>

      <p>The implication is that a woman who enters pregnancy with a TSH of 3.5 — technically within the "normal" range for the general population — may be functionally subclinical hypothyroid for pregnancy purposes, and that her obstetric outcomes and her child's neurodevelopmental trajectory may be adversely affected by that functional deficit.</p>

      <p>The TSH debate from Part 1 lands differently in the prenatal context. The stakes are not just individual quality of life but fetal brain development and pregnancy viability. The case for earlier intervention, more sensitive thresholds, and routine first-trimester thyroid screening is stronger here than anywhere else in thyroid medicine.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"The cost of this screening is trivial. The cost of not doing it — measured in miscarriages, preterm births, compromised neurodevelopment, and preventable autism risk — is not trivial."</p>
