    <section id="screening-failure" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Screening Failure</h2>

      <p>The American Thyroid Association recommends testing TSH levels in women who are actively trying to conceive if they have symptoms of thyroid disease, known risk factors, or a history of prior thyroid disease. This is not universal screening.</p>

      <p>The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) has historically recommended against universal thyroid screening in pregnancy, arguing that the evidence base for treating subclinical hypothyroidism in pregnant women without risk factors is insufficient to justify the cost and medicalization of routine screening.</p>

      <p>Both organizations are operating from the same evidence base and reaching different policy conclusions, which is itself instructive. The evidence that treating overt hypothyroidism in pregnancy improves outcomes is unambiguous. The evidence that treating subclinical hypothyroidism (TSH 2.5–4.0) in antibody-negative women without symptoms improves outcomes is less clear — randomized controlled trials have not consistently shown benefit, and one large RCT (the CATS trial) showed no significant improvement in child IQ at age 3 when levothyroxine treatment was started in the second trimester.</p>

      <p>The CATS trial's limitations, however, are material to this interpretation. Treatment began in the second trimester — after the window of maximum fetal thyroid hormone dependency, which is concentrated in the first trimester. Starting treatment after the horse has left the barn is not a valid test of whether earlier treatment would have been beneficial. The timing of intervention is central to whether it works, and the trials that fail to show benefit by intervening late are not evidence that early intervention fails.</p>

      <p>The November 2025 Israeli ASD study, the iodine deficiency resurgence data, the PFAS-thyroid-autism pathway, and the mechanistic literature on first-trimester thyroid hormone dependency all point toward a clinical policy that the guidelines have not adopted: universal first-trimester thyroid screening with TSH, free T4, and TPO antibodies for all pregnant women, combined with proactive iodine supplementation counseling.</p>

      <p>The cost of this screening is trivial. The cost of not doing it — measured in miscarriages, preterm births, compromised neurodevelopment, and preventable autism risk — is not trivial. It is simply borne by children who have no political voice, whose developmental deficits may not become apparent until years after the window for prevention has closed.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="sleep-deprivation-multiplier" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Sleep-Deprivation Multiplier</h2>

      <p>A specifically modern pregnancy risk factor deserves acknowledgment: the intersection of sleep deprivation with thyroid vulnerability during gestation. Pregnant women are, physiologically and socially, among the most sleep-deprived demographic in Western societies. First-trimester insomnia, third-trimester physical discomfort, and the cultural expectation that prenatal discomfort is normal and to be endured all contribute to chronic sleep insufficiency in pregnant women.</p>

      <p>Sleep deprivation, as established in the broader research literature, suppresses regulatory T-cell activity, increases pro-inflammatory cytokine production, and activates the HPA stress axis — all of which feed into the autoimmune activation and cortisol-mediated thyroid hormone suppression pathways described in Parts 1 and 2. In a pregnant woman who is marginally iodine-deficient, carrying a PFAS body burden from decades of prior exposure, with a gut microbiome reflecting years of antibiotic use and low-fiber diet, and sleeping six hours per night — the aggregate thyroid risk is not additive. It is potentially multiplicative. The entire system that is supposed to protect fetal neurodevelopment is under simultaneous stress from multiple directions.</p>

      <p>This is not alarmism. It is physiology. And it argues for a pregnancy care model that takes thyroid function, nutritional status, sleep, and environmental exposure as co-equal clinical priorities — not as peripheral concerns to be addressed, if at all, by a specialty referral after something goes demonstrably wrong.</p>
    </section>

